Some should be abandoned by seeing.

9
00:02:03,284 --> 00:02:06,527
So that was when we were discussing this whole business of not self.

10
00:02:07,427 --> 00:02:09,370
Should be abandoned by restraining.

11
00:02:09,409 --> 00:02:12,112
Abandoned by using.

12
00:02:12,353 --> 00:02:15,475
That was, you know, things like food and stuff like that.

13
00:02:16,176 --> 00:02:17,639
Abandoned by enduring.

14
00:02:17,699 --> 00:02:21,443
Yes, there are certain things that all we can do is bear with them until they pass.

15
00:02:22,364 --> 00:02:23,905
And then we avoid them.

16
00:02:25,907 --> 00:02:30,491
We avoid certain places that are too tempting for us.

17
00:02:30,978 --> 00:02:34,882
And now we have abandoned by removing.

18
00:02:36,604 --> 00:02:38,145
So let me just read the passage.

19
00:02:40,348 --> 00:02:43,592
What taints should be abandoned by removing?

20
00:02:45,634 --> 00:02:51,040
Here a Bhikkhu, remember the Bhikkhu refers to anybody listening, reflecting wisely.

21
00:02:51,140 --> 00:02:54,384
So don't forget he's very big on wise reflection.

22
00:02:56,546 --> 00:03:00,731
Does not tolerate an arisen thought of sensual desire.

23
00:03:01,471 --> 00:03:06,938
He abandons it, he removes it, he does away with it, he annihilates it.

24
00:03:07,860 --> 00:03:13,108
He does not tolerate an arisen thought of ill will, an arisen thought of cruelty.

25
00:03:13,830 --> 00:03:15,292
He does not tolerate it.

26
00:03:16,193 --> 00:03:21,360
He abandons it, he removes it, does away with them and annihilates them.

27
00:03:22,562 --> 00:03:25,486
While taints, vexation and fever

28
00:03:25,889 --> 00:03:37,425
So vexation, remember, is the vexation fever referred to the two sides of desire, wanting, not wanting, might arise in one who does not remove these thoughts.

29
00:03:37,627 --> 00:03:42,313
There are no taints, vexation or fever, in one who removes them.

30
00:03:42,995 --> 00:03:46,439
These are called the taints that should be abandoned by removing.

31
00:03:46,680 --> 00:03:53,871
So now we have to move again to a different discourse where this is explained in greater detail.

32
00:03:54,390 --> 00:03:58,695
So this is number Majjhima Nikaya, the middle end saying is number 19.

33
00:03:59,217 --> 00:04:01,439
And it's Dvideha Vittika.

34
00:04:01,460 --> 00:04:03,842
Now Vittika just means thinking.

35
00:04:03,983 --> 00:04:05,183
So that's important.

36
00:04:05,223 --> 00:04:07,247
Vittika just means thinking.

37
00:04:07,567 --> 00:04:10,991
OK, as opposed to emoting, thinking.

38
00:04:12,233 --> 00:04:14,795
So this is this is the blessed one.

39
00:04:15,889 --> 00:04:21,177
He was speaking again at Jetavana, Jeta's Grove.

40
00:04:21,197 --> 00:04:25,041
Remember the place that Anathapindika, this rich businessman, bought for him.

41
00:04:26,343 --> 00:04:41,862
And he says, Venerable Sir, they replied, the Blessed One said, before my enlightenment, while I was still only an unenlightened Bodhisattva, it occurred to me, supposing I divide my thoughts into two classes,

42
00:04:42,485 --> 00:04:48,524
Then I set on one side thoughts of sensual desire, thoughts of ill will and thoughts of cruelty.

43
00:04:49,045 --> 00:04:56,528
And I set on the other side thoughts of renunciation, thoughts of non-ill will and thoughts of non-cruelty.

44
00:04:57,233 --> 00:05:00,156
So here we have the Bodhisattva.

45
00:05:00,216 --> 00:05:09,511
Remember, that's what we call somebody who has made a determination to become a fully self-awakened Buddha.

46
00:05:09,531 --> 00:05:13,377
That's different from the Mahayana, where everybody takes the Bodhisattva vow.

47
00:05:14,899 --> 00:05:17,523
In Theravada, they're very specific.

48
00:05:21,749 --> 00:05:25,113
Sometimes people do it in this very lifetime.

49
00:05:25,464 --> 00:05:32,774
Others remember during their meditation that they've made this vow in the past life.

50
00:05:33,536 --> 00:05:39,764
Perhaps we can give you examples of that in some other time, but we'll stick to this discourse.

51
00:05:41,826 --> 00:05:51,439
So when he says, and set on the other five thoughts of renunciation, non-ill will and non-cruelty,

52
00:05:51,908 --> 00:05:56,334
The Buddha often likes the negative form telling you what's not there.

53
00:05:56,355 --> 00:06:02,644
So obviously here he's referring to metta, goodwill and compassion, not cruelty.

54
00:06:05,228 --> 00:06:08,713
As I abided thus, diligent, ardent and resolute.

55
00:06:08,733 --> 00:06:10,875
So we've come across this little trilogy before.

56
00:06:11,357 --> 00:06:13,961
Diligent, ardent and resolute.

57
00:06:14,781 --> 00:06:18,927
A thought of sensual desire arose in me and I understood thus.

58
00:06:19,668 --> 00:06:38,757
this thought of essential desire has arisen in me this leads to my own affliction to others affliction and to the affliction of both it obstructs wisdom causes difficulties and leads away from nibana this leads to my own affliction

59
00:06:39,562 --> 00:07:07,545
uh when he thought this leads to my own affliction it subsided in me in other words as soon as i recognized the thought was doing me harm the desire to indulge it began to fall away subsided when i considered that it leads to other people's affliction and then also that desire subsided in me well that's the compassion bit isn't it and when i considered

60
00:07:08,031 --> 00:07:13,677
This leads to the affliction of both in the same way it subsided in me, right?

61
00:07:13,697 --> 00:07:15,279
So there's your wise reflection.

62
00:07:15,300 --> 00:07:17,442
These are examples of wise reflection.

63
00:07:18,043 --> 00:07:23,168
You have a thought in your mind of some sensual desire or sexual desire, doesn't matter what it is.

64
00:07:23,709 --> 00:07:25,630
And you can see that it's obsessive.

65
00:07:26,192 --> 00:07:29,035
And if you hang on in there, it's just going to do you harm.

66
00:07:29,595 --> 00:07:35,682
And it's reflecting on the harm that it could possibly do to you that makes you want to let go of it.

67
00:07:35,922 --> 00:07:37,684
So then it'll subside.

68
00:07:38,052 --> 00:07:39,514
you're bringing up the opposite.

69
00:07:40,615 --> 00:07:53,252
So in the same way, if you have a sensual doubt which is going to hurt somebody else, like feeding their biscuits, then you have to see what a horrible thing that is, and the desire will subside.

70
00:07:53,954 --> 00:08:03,047
And when we do something that harms both myself and somebody else, then obviously that also helps us to let go of these thoughts.

71
00:08:06,908 --> 00:08:08,249
It obstructs wisdom.

72
00:08:08,329 --> 00:08:12,273
So remember, wisdom here is not an intellectual thing.

73
00:08:12,333 --> 00:08:13,533
It's a way of being.

74
00:08:14,113 --> 00:08:22,440
So it obstructs the wisdom, which is to live in harmony, to live with goodwill, to live with non-greed.

75
00:08:24,182 --> 00:08:27,545
Causes difficulties and obviously leads away from libana.

76
00:08:28,846 --> 00:08:35,952
So here, whenever the thought of sensual desire arose in me, I abandoned it, removed it and did away with it.

77
00:08:36,371 --> 00:09:03,020
now uh the same thing he said of course of uh all those thoughts around ill will and the thoughts around cruelty i abandoned it removed it did away with it now uh then he says there's a little passage here whatever a person frequently thinks and ponders upon that will become the inclination of his mind

78
00:09:03,743 --> 00:09:14,302
If he frequently thinks or ponders upon thoughts of sensual desire, he has abandoned the thought of renunciation to cultivate the thought of sensual desire.

79
00:09:15,205 --> 00:09:18,731
And then his mind inclines to thoughts of sensual desire.

80
00:09:19,774 --> 00:09:30,668
So this may seem a little obvious to us now, but in those days, I would have thought this is quite a revolutionary way of thinking about our psychology.

81
00:09:31,490 --> 00:09:38,398
So we know that when we keep thinking about the same thing, it becomes obsessive.

82
00:09:38,418 --> 00:09:44,264
It becomes a place where the mind seeks pleasure, seeks happiness.

83
00:09:44,865 --> 00:09:49,511
And then, of course, it is then expressed in the way we speak and what we do.

84
00:09:50,149 --> 00:09:58,221
And in so doing, of course, you're renouncing the path of renunciation.

85
00:09:58,561 --> 00:10:05,169
Now, always remember, when we talk about the path of renunciation, it's not the same as self-mortification.

86
00:10:05,190 --> 00:10:08,094
We're not blaming the body for its appetite.

87
00:10:09,335 --> 00:10:17,405
What we're trying to let go of is our obsessiveness around food, obsessiveness around sex, and so on and so forth.

88
00:10:17,857 --> 00:10:21,383
And that obsessiveness is what we're renouncing.

89
00:10:21,504 --> 00:10:22,585
We're not indulging it.

90
00:10:23,005 --> 00:10:24,427
How do we indulge these things?

91
00:10:24,668 --> 00:10:26,451
Through our thinking, through imagination.

92
00:10:27,111 --> 00:10:29,195
And it excites the heart, you see.

93
00:10:29,796 --> 00:10:33,321
Remember, all these desires begin in the heart, the heart base.

94
00:10:34,803 --> 00:10:37,126
And that's what we have to recognize here.

95
00:10:37,687 --> 00:10:44,337
What the Buddha is pushing away, abandoning, annihilating, is thoughts.

96
00:10:44,722 --> 00:10:52,921
He's not suggesting here that you should also try to annihilate a feeling, your emotional, your heart state.

97
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:53,663
Far from it.

98
00:10:54,264 --> 00:11:03,745
We know from the discourse on how to establish right mindfulness that he wants us to actually go in there to feel those feelings, feel feelings in feelings.

